## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that must change for .NET 8:

| API | Problem on .NET 8 | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Cancellable work loop |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable | Blocking call interruption |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Works, but can't be cancelled cooperatively | Blocking call interruption |

There's also a **pre-existing race condition**: multiple `Enqueue` calls can fire `Set()` but `Reset()` clears the signal before all items are drained, losing events.

---

### Migrated Code (CancellationToken + Channel)

The idiomatic .NET 8 replacement uses `Channel<T>`, which eliminates the manual lock, queue, event, and the race condition entirely:

```csharp
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Channels;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();     // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline
        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask;
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Old | New | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `Channel<string>` | Thread-safe producer-consumer with built-in backpressure; eliminates the lost-signal race |
| `Thread` + `Thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` | Uses the thread pool; returns an awaitable `Task` for clean shutdown |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_channel.Writer.Complete()` | Signals the reader to drain remaining items and exit |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.CancelAfter(5s)` | Hard deadline via cooperative cancellation — throws `OperationCanceledException` inside `ReadAllAsync` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` (implicit) | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | The new exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `void Stop()` | `async Task StopAsync()` | Awaitable so callers know when shutdown is truly complete |

---

### If you must keep synchronous threads

If your codebase can't go async, here's the synchronous equivalent using `WaitHandle.WaitAny`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };
        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either a new event OR cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the original race condition)
            List<string> snapshot;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                snapshot = new List<string>(_queue);
                _queue.Clear();
            }

            foreach (var item in snapshot)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
        _cts.Dispose();
        // No Thread.Abort — if it hasn't exited, the thread
        // will exit at the next cancellation check
    }
}
```

Key point: `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle })` replaces both `Thread.Interrupt` (wakes the blocked thread) and `Thread.Abort` (signals termination).

---

### Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | If `Handle(item)` takes 30 seconds, cancellation won't fire until it returns. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle` if it does lengthy work. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers. Always dispose in `Stop`/`StopAsync`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate everywhere else. |
| **The original lost-signal bug** | The old code calls `Reset()` before `Dequeue()` — if two items are enqueued quickly, the second signal is lost. Both solutions above fix this by draining all items. |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** | Even if you only removed `Abort`, you must also replace `Interrupt` (`SYSLIB0046`). |

I recommend the `Channel<T>` approach — it's the modern .NET idiom for exactly this pattern and eliminates an entire class of threading bugs.
